msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.eig:50
msgid ":obj:`scipy.linalg.schur`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.eig:51
msgid "Best choice for unitary and other non-Hermitian normal matrices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.eig:55
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.eig:56
msgid ""
"Broadcasting rules apply, see the `numpy.linalg` documentation for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.eig:59
msgid ""
"This is implemented using the ``_geev`` LAPACK routines which compute the "
"eigenvalues and eigenvectors of general square arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.eig:62
msgid ""
"The number `w` is an eigenvalue of `a` if there exists a vector `v` such "
"that ``a @ v = w * v``. Thus, the arrays `a`, `eigenvalues`, and "
"`eigenvectors` satisfy the equations ``a @ eigenvectors[:,i] = "
"eigenvalues[i] * eigenvectors[:,i]`` for :math:`i \\in \\{0,...,M-1\\}`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.eig:67
msgid ""
"The array `eigenvectors` may not be of maximum rank, that is, some of the "
"columns may be linearly dependent, although round-off error may obscure that "
"fact. If the eigenvalues are all different, then theoretically the "
"eigenvectors are linearly independent and `a` can be diagonalized by a "
"similarity transformation using `eigenvectors`, i.e, ``inv(eigenvectors) @ a "
"@ eigenvectors`` is diagonal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.eig:74
msgid ""
"For non-Hermitian normal matrices the SciPy function `scipy.linalg.schur` is "
"preferred because the matrix `eigenvectors` is guaranteed to be unitary, "
"which is not the case when using `eig`. The Schur factorization produces an "
"upper triangular matrix rather than a diagonal matrix, but for normal "
"matrices only the diagonal of the upper triangular matrix is needed, the "
"rest is roundoff error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.eig:81
msgid ""
"Finally, it is emphasized that `eigenvectors` consists of the *right* (as in "
"right-hand side) eigenvectors of `a`. A vector `y` satisfying ``y.T @ a = z "
"* y.T`` for some number `z` is called a *left* eigenvector of `a`, and, in "
"general, the left and right eigenvectors of a matrix are not necessarily the "
"(perhaps conjugate) transposes of each other."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.eig:88
